<br>
Mine is Tasslehoff  Burrfoot. He cracks me up, but he has the soul of a angel. I would like to say I strive to be like him. He looks at the world through child's eyes, and sees things in a different way than everyone else. He is always finding the fun, even in the most droll, but can be serious when he really needs to. He is a light in a world of darkness, and a true hero. He is funny, loving, and ultimately.. everything I think I would like to be.<br>
<br>
What about yours?<br>
<br>
Kuladen <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.inkbard.com/art/kuladensig.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lest@firionavie>Lest</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 274<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/1/03 4:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm57.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=233.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> So many... </span><hr size=1> I'll second Tasslehoff as a favorite. I used to carry a quote from him around on a slip of paper for when things got awful: <br>
<br>
&quot;Still, we have to keep trying and hoping. That’s what’s important, the trying and the hoping. Maybe that’s most important of all.&quot;<br>
<br>
That whole cast was great, though. <br>
<br>
Also on my list: Robert B. Parker's Spenser. I strive to be that comfortable in myself and firm in my convictions (usually failing miserably, of course). He was my hero to the point I took up boxing because of him. To this day I still talk like that sometimes, tossing out random quotes and doing bad Bogart impressions. <br>
<br>
Lestat's another favorite of mine. His closing statement in &quot;Memnoch the Devil&quot; is one of my favorite, most self-absorbed lines I've ever read. <br>
<br>
